{"cursor":"36949","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nWhile the presence of any mass bends the path of light passing near it, this\neffect rarely produces the giant arcs and multiple images associated with strong\ngravitational lensing. Most lines of sight in the universe are thoroughly in the\nweak lensing regime, in which the deflection is impossible to detect in a single\nbackground source. However, even in these cases, the presence of the foreground\nmass can be detected, by way of a systematic alignment of background sources\naround the lensing mass. 'Weak gravitational lensing' is thus an intrinsically\nstatistical measurement, but it provides a way to measure the masses of\nastronomical objects without requiring assumptions about their composition or\ndynamical state.\n","linknr":484,"url":"Cosmic_shear","recorded":1362891794,"links":52,"instances":["optics","mathematics","astronomy","mathematics","geometry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Gravitational lensing"],"headings":["Methodology","Weak lensing by clusters of galaxies","Galaxy-galaxy lensing","Cosmic shear","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/A_Horseshoe_Einstein_Ring_from_Hubble.JPG/220px-A_Horseshoe_Einstein_Ring_from_Hubble.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Shapenoise.svg/400px-Shapenoise.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Gravitational-lensing-3d.png/400px-Gravitational-lensing-3d.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/2/6/2268b81be746a242e2c0e1c6c935b6a8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Bullet_cluster_lensing.jpg/300px-Bullet_cluster_lensing.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/e/8/1e890ea47411badeaf801399ede3f037.png","//u